https://forge.autodesk.com/en/docs/bim360/v1/reference/http/projects-project_id-users-import-POST  
for adding project admins and project users.
resources.name: Project User - EMEA

resources.description:
Adds users (project admin and project user) to a project. You can add up to 50 users per call. We recommend using this endpoint as an alternative to https://forge.autodesk.com/en/docs/bim360/v1/reference/http/projects-project_id-users-POST 

To add users to an account (account user), see https://forge.autodesk.com/en/docs/bim360/v1/reference/http/users-POST 

You can specify the following details about the user:

The user’s access level for the project (admin or user).
The company the user is assigned to for the project.
The industry roles assigned to the user for the project.
The user’s email address.
Note that this endpoint is version 2 (v2) - you need to use ../v2/.. in the URI.
resources.name: Project User Import - US

resources.description: Retrieves the profile information about an end user, including the user’s name and workflow role, as well as details about whether the user has permissions to create issues. However it does not currently provide full information about a users permissions. For example, whether a user has basic, view all, create, view and create, or full control permissions.
resources.name: Issues User

resources.description:
Retrieves information about all the BIM 360 issues in a project, including details about their associated comments and attachments. To get more detailed information about a single issue, for example, details about whether attachments have been added to an issue since a specific date, see GET issues/:id.

You can retrieve both document-related (pusphin) issues and project-related issues. For details about pushpin issues, see the Create Pushpin Issues in Your App and Render Pushpin Issues in Your App tutorials.

To verify whether an issue is document-related (pusphin) or project-related, check the target_urn attribute in the response. If the issue is project-related the target_urn will be assigned a null value, if the issue is document-related, it will be assigned an ID.

BIM 360 issues are managed either in the BIM 360 Document Management module or the BIM 360 Field Management module.
resources.name: Issues

resources.description:
Adds a BIM 360 issue to a project. You can create both document-related (pushpin) issues, and project-related issues. For details about how to create pushpin issues, see the Create Pushpin Issues in Your App tutorial.

BIM 360 issues are managed either in the BIM 360 Document Management module or the BIM 360 Field Management module.

The following users can create issues:

Project admins
Project members who are assigned either create, view and create, or full control Management permissions. For more details, open the Project Admin module and see the Services tab.
To verify whether a user can create issues for a specific project, call GET users/me and verify that the quality_issues section includes the new object.
resources.name: Issues

resources.description:
Updates a BIM 360 issue.

BIM 360 issues are managed either in the BIM 360 Document Management module or the BIM 360 Field Management module.

The following users can update issues:

Project admins
Project members who are assigned either create, view and create, or full control Field Management permissions. For more details, open the Project Admin module and see the Services tab.
To verify whether a user can update issues for a specific project, call GET users/me and verify that the quality_issues section includes the new object.

To verify which attributes the user can update, call GET issues/:id and check the permitted_attributes and permitted_statuses lists.
resources.name: Issues

resources.description:
Retrieves detailed information about a single BIM 360 issue. For example, details about whether attachments have been added to an issue since a specific time. For general information about all the issues in a project, see GET issues.

You can retrieve both document-related (pusphin) issues and project-related issues. For details about pushpin issues, see the Create Pushpin Issues in Your App and Render Pushpin Issues in Your App tutorials.

To verify whether an issue is document-related (pushpin) or project-related, check the target_urn attribute in the response. If the issue is project-related the target_urn will be assigned a null value, if the issue is document-related, it will be assigned an ID.

BIM 360 issues are managed either in the BIM 360 Document Management module or the BIM 360 Field Management module.
resources.name: Issue

To retrieve the comments associated with all issues in a project, call GET issues with the include=comments query string parameter.
resources.name: Issues Comments

resources.description:
Retrieves a list of supported issue types (e.g., quality and safety) and issue subtypes (e.g., work to complete and pre-punch list) that you can allocate to an issue. By default, the response only includes issues types. To also include issue subtypes in the response, use the include=subtypes query string parameter.

To verify which attributes the user can update, call GET issues/:id and check the permitted_attributes and permitted_statuses lists.

Note that issue type and subtype IDs are unique for each project.

resources.description:
Retrieves information about all the BIM 360 Field Management checklists in a project, including details about their statuses, priorities, and assignees. To get more information about a single checklist, for example, details about checklist items, sections and attachments, see GET instances/:id.

Filtering

You can configure the response payload by setting up filter, pagination and sorting parameters. You can also specify which types of data appear in the response.

Filtering follows one of the following formats:

param[<fieldName>]=<matchValue>
  
param=<matchValue>
resources.name: Instances

resources.description:
Retrieves detailed information about a single BIM 360 Field Management checklist (instance). For example, details about checklist items, sections and attachments. To retrieve a detailed response, you need to use the include query string parameter. For information about all the checklists in a project, see GET instances. If the response payload includes data about the checklist’s sections, items, and attachments, you can reconstruct a checklist from the data by linking between the checklist hierarchy in the relationship objects, by following these instuctions:

Find the list of checklist sections in the data.relationships.sections.data array, and note the type (instance_sections) and id for each section.

Find the items that are associated with each section by searching for the section objects in the included array, using the section’s type and id you found in the previous step. In the relationships object in the included section object you can find the list of items for that section. Note the type and id for each item (included.sections.relationships.items).

Find the attachments that are associated with each item by searching for the item objects in the included array, using the item’s type and id you found in the previous step. In the relationships object in the included item object you can find the list of attachments for that item.

Note that the order of the sections, items, and attachments are determined by the index attribute.
resources.name: Instances Id

resources.description:
Retrieves information about all the BIM 360 Field Management templates in a project, including details about the items, sections, and attachments in the template. To get information about a single template, see GET templates/:id.

Filtering

You can configure the response payload by setting up filter, pagination and sorting parameters. You can also specify which types of data appear in the response.

Filtering follows one of the following formats:

param[<fieldName>]=<matchValue>
  
param=<matchValue>
resources.name: Templates

resources.description: Retrieves information about a specific BIM 360 Field Management template, including details about the items, sections, and attachments in the template. To get information about all the templates in the project, see GET templates.
resources.name: Templates id
